b.io/crossreads/data/allographs/types/greek-Ω-type2.3.2.html",{"_":150,"ana":151,"ref":152},"chiselled","#execution.chiselled","http://www.eagle-network.eu/voc/writing/lod/1",{"lettering":154,"dimensions":155},"The lettering is tight, both in between letters and in interlinear spaces. The first two lines are larger and more spaced, though not necessarily more precise in execution. Alpha appears with both a straight and a curved crossbar. Interchangeable use of four-bar and lunate sigma, often in the same line, often close together. Interchangeable use of square and lunate epsilon, same variability and position as with sigma. There is occasional omission of the middle bar of a lunate epsilon, particularly in between two sigmas, resulting visually in the combination CCC. This occurs both at the beginning and end of lines, and does not seem to correspond to textual cues. Omega is mostly rhomboid or ovoid, occasionally round, though the few round instances seem to be an execution issue with the ovoid variant rather than a stylistic choice. ",[156,163,168],{"type":157,"l":158,"from":159,"to":160,"h":161,"unit":162},"letterHeight","Line 1-3","line1","line3","15-20","mm",{"type":157,"l":164,"from":165,"to":166,"h":167,"unit":162},"Line 4-47","line4","line47","10",{"type":169,"l":170,"from":159,"to":171,"unit":162},"interlinear","Interlineation line 1 to 2","line2",{"_":173,"notBefore":174,"notAfter":175,"evidence":176},"(Later) second or first century BCE (Dubois and Cordiano suggest 1st cent. BCE)",-200,-51,"lettering",[178,182],{"_":179,"type":180,"ref":181},"Phintias","ancient","http://pleiades.stoa.org/places/462424",{"_":183,"type":184,"ref":185},"Licata","modern","http://sws.geonames.org/2524393",[187],[188,189],37.10267,13.93972,"Italy","Sicily",{"_":193,"role":194,"ref":19},"Museo Archeologico della Badia","museum",{"_":196,"mainLang":197,"languages":198},"Ancient Greek","grc",[196],{"n":200,"url":201,"height":202,"width":203,"desc":204,"surfaceType":205},"screen",